Barack Obama will receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president.
U.S. President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
He will receive a diploma, a medal and a check for $1.4 million, among other things, for his extraordinary efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The head of the White House will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife Michelle and will be busy.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of the committee, which selected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The pair are scheduled to meet with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president, but only the third to receive the award directly from the office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will speak about the Afghan war when accepting the award.
The president does not want to avoid this topic because he realizes that he is taking the prize as a president who is currently fighting in two countries.
He increased the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which will not forget to highlight any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He plans to give them to charity, but has not yet decided on a specific charity.
The packed program will then take the president to a banquet, where, in addition to the Norwegian king and queen, there will also be a prime minister and another 250 invited guests.
From the beginning, Obama has been rather cautious about the price.
He said, for example, that he felt that he did not fully deserve it.
He also reiterated several times that this is not just a prize for him, but for all who strive for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said it was a "call to action".
