Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical how schoolboy Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the stupidest, on the Afghan issue.
When he finally sweated out his much-anticipated Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it from Bush’s Iraqi script three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not even hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: "A New Way Forward."
Three years ago, he himself criticized Bush’s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to civil war-torn Iraq as an “irresponsible and disastrous decision.”
The months that followed, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of the field commanders, was the only possible and successful one, so much so that there is no talk of Iraq in the news reports today.
It did not improve Bush’s reputation, but objectively left his successor a much more grateful starting position than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was again asked to increase the military contingent by field commanders, in particular the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, even despite the subordination habits, harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House.
He asked for 40,000 men so he could break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he could not think of anything better, so at least he deceived the general by 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to squeeze out of Europe the promise of another 5,000, although he himself originally counted on at least 10.
The most problematic of all Obama’s strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in as little as 18 months and end the process within three years. The entire Obama Doctrine raises more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a half-increase will yield the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honoring agreements.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are being kept.
Under these conditions, the Afghan security forces are preparing poorly, accustomed to changing the master every day according to how it suits them.
The political institutions, even if formally established, will remain only a village of obscurity, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult given the opacity of the situation, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even building an "accessible state", which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, does not seem too real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy strikes with its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of an explosion.
To believe that the soldiers sent into the war turmoil for the purpose of "soon returning home" will cause a miracle done here, can only be a truly romantic soul, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is a sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will perceive it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit has shown that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is declining.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically interfering in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the difficult question before the United States is whether to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will need to be answered at a time when, according to Obama, America will embark on a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential election, and therefore enough time left for him to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
