Metal carboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, the researchers come up with new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metal carboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Traitorous and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is an HIV protein that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV cleavage, no mature infectious viral particles would arise.
If we stop HIV protease, we will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cells (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of anti-HIV proteases was tested in a test tube and also against its resistant variants obtained from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of metallocarboranes on the normal variant of the enzyme is not as strong as with clinically used drugs, but does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
