The management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence was useless...
For more than a decade, the behavior of the management of large companies towards employees has been reminiscent of the approach of companies to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about co-workers identifying themselves with the "values" determined from the mountain, as it was before, when it was necessary to impose on the consumer products that came from the ideas of the heads of factory technicians.
By making the customer the center of business companies, the marketing revolution has leveled the strategy of conquering the market in the right direction... even though authoritarian efforts to force products other than customer preferences regularly return!
The passive attitude of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only a visible part of a much more widespread general phenomenon, which mainly affects managerial cadres.
This demobilization adversely affects the development of all intellectual functions of society, including research and development, and more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires from all stakeholders (...) an active approach and the ability to anticipate" and demands from employees commitments that are completely at odds with the revenues of authoritarian management.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that aims to put workers at the centre of business as well as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls.
Will internal opinion polls – like a questionnaire submitted to Orange employees – contribute to a revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
Mainly because I have already convinced myself that in the face of a new situation, the structure after various turns will return preferably to what it has always done!
Furthermore, because authoritarianism, as one of the pathologies of power, increases in proportion to the severity of its own failures.
And finally, because most managers have a simplified view of human behavior.
Because they are university graduates for engineers, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
For reasons of convenience, they adopt the old behavioral theory, now revived by "neurosciences" from the USA and widely disseminated without much knowledge by scientific institutes and the media.
A recent Ipsos survey on Figaro.fr showed that it is possible to move the "levers" (sic) of managers' involvement, which only establishes managers in their position of mechanical control, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors.
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes the adoption of the final vision of human behavior.
Incorporating a basic insight into all management intentions and practices: For employees, commitments to the business will only be possible if they appear to be a clear means to achieve their dreams, ambitions and projects.
At present, this concept of employee motivation is only dealt with by the study Motivational functional analysis.
These studies have shown that they evaluate their businesses on the basis of a predetermined doxy, which will allow them, through the image that tells about the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their life goals.
By identifying and measuring these mobilisation factors, managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resource management "on the right track".
This creates a breeding ground for the development of solid and effective economic intelligence.
In a speech from Oslo, Obama won praise from the right.
On Friday, the American right welcomed a speech delivered by Barack Obama the day before in Oslo, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner had defended the concept of a “just war” against the enemies of the United States.
