Cradle of Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: The animal, two meters long and 1.50 meters high, ran on two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short forelimbs with sickle claws and a long tail.
If this species lived a few million years later, there would be nothing extraordinary.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in the Thursday edition of the journal Science write that Tawa hallae was, however, one of the first dinosaurs with these body features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry region of the supercontinent Pangaea.
Tawa opens a new window on the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about kinship relationships, expansion, and the signs of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavations at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for triassic sediments, according to team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The finding confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the solar god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual finding: "Fossils of dinosaurs from the Triassic are very rare, usually only individual fragments can be found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
This finding is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are not complete, so the attribution of pradinosaurs is often disputed.
Experts discuss, for example, when lizards were divided into three most important developmental lines: carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and also birds, "long-necked" quadruped sauropods and their relatives, and herbivores, for example, Trinithischia, and herbivores.
Tawa hallae is, after analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues, the original therapod.
It exhibits an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers have found evidence of air sacs, which even the descendants of theropods have birds.
Thanks to the air sacs, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related lineage of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation has probably already created a common ancestor of both groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists have deduced that lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of development soon separated and spread from South America to all continents, which at that time, as the supercontinent of Pangaea, formed a uniform mass of the earth.
It would also speak for the fact that the team, along with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related, theropods.
The three cannot come from a common, immigrant ancestor, the scientists argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, the Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in today’s Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His hypothesis could put together a distorted picture, because in South America very many primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved, while on other continents they are rarely found.
How the dinosaurs proved that they evolved from a relatively rare lineage of reptiles to the ruling vertebrates of the earth during the Earth's Middle Ages remains a puzzle.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and flying lizards, and countless other lizards.
Around the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world and many new species evolved, while relatives became extinct and the Triassic and Jurassic interfaces.
The success story didn’t last forever.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction that dinosaurs happened to survive, but reptiles didn't.
Or the dinosaurs adapted better, so they could squeeze out the competition.
The history of success did not last forever.
About 150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped another group of animals that also evolved in the Triassic and has lived in the shadows ever since: mammals.
