About one percent of people get schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is the second most commonly treated disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most affected individuals can no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, they become in an awakened state that can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship illusions, or the illusion of persecution.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices - voices that command, comment or conduct dialogues.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The affected person is not able to distinguish the important from the unimportant, the brain can not filter out disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, psychosis opens the flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the Department of General Psychiatry at the University Clinic in Heidelberg.
Schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning aimed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, becomes, like in a dream, overwhelmed by events and cannot actively form them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is not usually possible with them, ghosts are a terrible reality, awakening is excluded.
Once in a Lifetime Experience a Hallucination
Unlike in a dream, Fuchss says, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality that one perceives in psychosis remains fundamentally preserved."
Deviant thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in a real framework.
Scientists are still puzzled as to why our brains are doing this.
“Exceptional states can cause any person to lose touch with reality in the short term,” Fuchs said.
However, not everyone develops psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists assume that the affected persons have minimal brain damage.
We believe that in the early stages of development there will be damage to the neuronal maturation of the brain, for example, viral diseases of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a puzzle as to how the neuronal system will malfunction, which has not manifested itself in this way for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis, if there is a disposition to it.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brain shuts down
It is crazy that psychotronics suffer from hallucinations, and in order to get rid of them, they swallow expensive medicines, others give money for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from L<0xC3><0xBC>beck.
Whether illusions are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a question of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he interpreted his results in his book "Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf" (The Unreal World in Our Head).
Hallucinations belong to the typical accompanying phenomena of psychoses, but also to surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline personality or depression, often diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's or brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, the brain of a healthy person itself also hallucinates.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of the contents of thoughts that are normally suppressed.
They occur when the parts of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are overactive or under-repressed; when our brain shuts down, or when there is a lack of stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the withdrawal of stimuli, stress, worries about love or other exceptional conditions.
In more recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported having experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the local grammar school.
A perfectly normal girl, actually.
If it wasn't for the shapes and voices.
At break times, she may be approached by a cooing with long, dark hair.
When she answers, her classmates look at her in surprise - no one but her sees and hears this boy.
This shy girl is considered a dreamer, but Sarah K. does not dream, she knows that.
He is awake, he hears and sees the boy, just as he hears and sees the girl sitting next to him in the bench.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
“Am I crazy?” he sometimes asks.
But he knows that this boy and other delusions are not real and will disappear again.
At night, the appearances are rather depressing
Often, the illusions are a burden.
When she is sitting in the classroom, she cannot watch the lesson many times, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just presenting a new classmate, but he explains the mathematical equation to everyone else audible and visible on the blackboard.
At night, the apparitions are rather depressing.
When he waits in his dark room for sleep, which rarely comes too late, he often cannot tell whether he is awake or already asleep, whether the images he sees are grimacing, or a girl with bleeding cuts on her arms and legs appears before her with her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, he's yelling at the characters.
She doesn't tell her parents or friends about it, they'd think she was crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows for sure that she hasn't gone crazy.
Illusions are also the art of despair.
If someone is socially isolated or their stimuli are taken away, they are likely to have hallucinations, Kasten says.
I think that the brain does not have enough work and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she had called her father since she was thinking for herself was not her own father.
Because visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same brain regions that process real sensations and sounds, it's hard for the affected, like Sarah K., to distinguish between delusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is also displayed there.
Hallucinations are also images that allow the brain to form, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also evaluates night dreams as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
Compared to schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
The boundary between dream and hallucination
In our world too conscious, the imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic of the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in D<0xC3><0xBC>sseldorf.
Psychosis is a severe, agonizing disease, but it also brings positivity, creativity - a delusion is also an art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhardt studied the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of altered dream consciousness.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictional dreams that the person concerned considers to be real and cannot even distinguish them retroactively from the waking state.
Oneiroidal state of consciousness occurs in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis in full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and himself, for example, a persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces life-threatening real situations with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between dream and hallucination.
Because in reality it is not possible to handle a situation, there will be a change of worlds, but the real situation will become present in the imagination.
An intense form of sense support and the transference of the senses into some intolerable situation that enables us humans to pass, in an instant, into a loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memories
Also art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen describes his one-eyed experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" (The Exchange of Hearts) as a saving action of the soul.
He was 49 years old when, after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, his consciousness set out on a several-day journey, with his body lying motionless in an intensive care unit.
Claussen plunges into the world he has created, visiting strange times and places: he becomes an old man strapped to a bed, in a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility, which produces intoxicating substances from blood.
He is kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle to his homeland, surfs the firn in the Alps on a hospital bed, and meets a Korean mobster.
Immerse yourself completely in the imaginary story, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner paths are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a different state, it describes your experience.
Contrary to dreams, the memories of those mental journeys are still clear after years and in insignificant details.
Even brighter and more intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience shatters the horizon of our other true experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug intoxication show how fragile even in the waking state our inner images of external reality are.
Any change in the state of consciousness, concludes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to the deformation of what we call reality."
It’s a fact that can also be enriching.
Snow can come.
