75% of working mothers have work-related maternity problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of a study 'Fertility and Career of Spanish Women' conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labor market because of motherhood.
The study points out that at the beginning of cohabitation, there are many differences in opinions about the number of children depending on whether they work or not, as well as on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with a partner earlier, give birth to their first child earlier, and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, postpone partnership and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years since the beginning of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving their stable employment and therefore had to postpone cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of occupation also has a strong impact on motherhood, although it has less impact on the time of starting cohabitation with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage and the birth of a child is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group 35 to 49 years, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 and 32.1.
“There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with primary education get married and have their first child before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education go the opposite way, preferring to get a stable job, before marriage and the birth of their first child,” Delgado said.
