The auxiliary system at the handbrake is already a mandatory equipment.
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock system, it will also be with ESP stability control, auxiliary handbrake systems, all this will become mandatory equipment for European cars.
In fact, they are already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest, a deadline is set for the elimination of the deficiency, which is February 2011.
The measure introduced in the EU aims to increase pedestrian protection, while it works in such a way that it can help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary handbrake system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects when the driver steps on.
But it is not always possible to maintain this pressure until the end.
According to a study by auto parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers who have an accident have not braked before a collision, and half of them have not fully used the brake force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the braking system to the maximum, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of device, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatalities could be prevented per year.
Reducing this number will be even more significant—calculated to avoid one in four accidents with an impact on people—after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, the vehicle will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) detects obstacles and reports them to the driver, in addition to light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help to increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the device will act as intensively as possible on the brake and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
