Internet auction of crashed vehicles
Last October, the Solera Group bought Autoonline, an online base for selling cars and motorcycles or special vehicles after an insurance event.
The operation assumed the subscription of 59.5 million euros out of 85% of the company’s capital, which could be expanded next year by the remaining 15%.
The aim of the purchase was to provide more value-added services to customers with access to a huge international market.
This valuation and buying and selling service is guaranteed exclusively to professionals in the sector such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, repair shops, spare parts sales and professional dealers who have to register before operations begin.
The platform was founded in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations across Europe, including 500,000 in Germany.
Among the main markets stands out Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
The site currently has more than 1,500 registered sellers and 4,000 connoisseurs.
It manages 3,000 daily ads and about 100 new ads are added to the Spanish market every day.
Under Spanish law, a car whose chassis number has been decommissioned cannot be put back into service, but can be used as a source of spare parts that have not been damaged.
Vehicles with historical value may be allowed to operate, even if they have been decommissioned, after a preliminary procedure.
Service budget in four steps
With the Auda-Taller tool, Audatex guarantees that the user gets the budget in only four steps: vehicle identification, finding a spare part, creating a budget and generating a budget.
Ease of use is an essential condition for these systems, especially for the conviction of older professionals who are more or less reserved in the use of new management techniques.
The database contains 1,034 vehicles, including 666 tourist, 109 off-road, 137 motorcycles, 78 deliveries and 44 trucks.
Naturally, for use, you need a computer with an Internet connection.
After identifying the model to be repaired, using the chassis number, a real graphical representation of the model appears, and then the necessary spare part is selected.
The user can include variables such as labor price, surcharges or discounts, and then print and hand over to the customer.
AudaTaller is not a valuation tool like AudaPlus, but rather a reference catalogue.
The main difference between the two systems is that it is service-oriented and does not include a workforce estimate.
The cost of using this tool for the workshop is 350 euros per year, which the customer can finance.
At present, Audatex is working to ensure that these images are three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics welcome, because it allows, for example, to select a door and turn it to display the inner side.
